impact:
• **Cost headwinds for new utility‑scale projects.**  The mandatory 4.58 % gross‑revenue charge is materially higher than the sliding‑scale (often <3 %) fees Interior adopted in its 2024 Renewable‑Energy Rule, and the annual 3 % escalator locks in real growth even if power prices fall.  Developers are likely to re‑rank sites toward private or state trust lands, slowing federal‑land build‑out.  :contentReference[oaicite:0]{index=0}
• **Revenue upside—at a climate‑policy trade‑off.**  Treasury receipts rise, but Interior’s own rulemaking record shows lower fees were intended to accelerate deployment toward the 25‑GW federal‑land target.  Re‑tightening fees could jeopardise that momentum, conflicting with administration decarbonisation deadlines.  :contentReference[oaicite:1]{index=1}
• **Financing and insurance risks.**  Automatic lease cancellation after 90 days of delinquency, without a cure period tied to force‑majeure events, elevates lender risk.  Higher cost of capital may be passed through to rate‑payers or erode project pipelines.
• **Signal for multiple‑use conflicts.**  A modest 10 % discount for co‑location may be too small to incentivise livestock‑grazing or recreation overlaps, undercutting congressional intent to balance uses on public lands.
